You can&#39;t. If an exception is thrown the normal flow of the code will be interrupted and thus the second exception will never be thrown. Instead you&#39;d have to do both checks and throw a &quot;combined&quot; exception at the end.

For example, you could do something like this:

    List&lt;String&gt; errors = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
  
    //check the name
    if (nameNew == null || nameNew.trim().isEmpty()) {
        errors.add(&quot;name should not be empty&quot;);
    }

    //check the points
    if (pointsNew &lt; 3 || pointsNew &gt; 20) {
        errors.add(&quot;points should be between 3 and 20&quot;);
    }

    //if there are errors, throw an exception
    if(!errors.isEmpty()) {
      //for simplicity we&#39;ll use IllegalArgumentException and concat the messages with a newline 
      //in a realworld application it would probably be best to use a custom exception and keep the list of errors
      throw new IllegalArgumentException(String.join(&quot;\n&quot;, errors));
    }

When an exception is thrown, processing will jump to wherever that exception is caught.

Because the try block is around your *call* to Info(), once Info() throws an exception (the first time, in it&#39;s call to setName()), you&#39;re going to move into the catch block in your main() function and be out of the Info() function entirely, so Info() will never reach its second line where it would have called setPoints().

If you want to catch both of them, you would need to ensure that Info remains active and resumes processing, which means that&#39;s where you want the exceptions to be handled.

    public Info(String n, int p) {
        try {
            setName(n);
        catch (IllegalArgumentException exc ) {
            System.out.println(exc.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            setPoints(p);
        catch (IllegalArgumentException exc ) {
            System.out.println(exc.getMessage());
        }
    }

In this version, Info() is handling the exception from its call to setName(), and then ***after*** that catch moving on to calling setPoints(), which may also have an exception that Info() will also handle.

With this scenario, Info() itself will never throw an IllegalArgumentException, since it&#39;s already handled the ones that can occur during it, so you wouldn&#39;t need the try/catch for in in your main() function.

EDIT:  
Ok, I missed the class name and the fact that this is in the constructor.  What I said initially would be valid if Info() was a regular function being called.  But with a constructor, you may want an Exception to tell you it wasn&#39;t able to initialize correctly.

But the main point still applies.  If you want to see both errors, you need to ensure that the constructor calls both setter functions.  You could add tracking of the fact that there was at least one error, and re-throw the exception so that your main sees that the constructor failed:

    public Info(String n, int p) {
        boolean failure = false;
        try {
            setName(n);
        catch (IllegalArgumentException exc ) {
            System.out.println(exc.getMessage());
            failure = true;
        }

        try {
            setPoints(p);
        catch (IllegalArgumentException exc ) {
            System.out.println(exc.getMessage());
            failure = true;
        }

        if (failure) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;invalid parameters&quot;);
        }
    }

