You can use [Object.entries()][1] and [reduce()][2] to do that.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const obj = {
      A: {
        B: [0, 0, 0, 0]
      },
      D: {
        B: [0, 0, 0, 0],
        C: [0, 0, 0, 0]
      }
    };

    var result = Object.entries(obj).reduce((acc, [key, value]) =&gt; {
      Object.entries(value).forEach(([subKey, subValue]) =&gt; {
        acc[key + &#39; - &#39; + subKey] = subValue;
      });

      return acc;
    }, {});

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/entries
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/reduce

Basic solution
--------------

One possibility:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const convert = (obj) =&gt; 
      Object.entries (obj)
        .reduce ((a, [k1, v]) =&gt; Object .keys (v) .reduce ((a, k2) =&gt; ({
          ...a,
          [`${k1} - ${k2}`]: v [k2]
        }), a), {})

    const obj = {A: { B: [0, 0, 0, 0] }, D: {B: [0, 0, 0, 0], C: [0, 0, 0, 0]}}

    console .log (convert (obj))

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


Deeper paths
------------

But it wouldn&#39;t be terribly hard to create a version which worked recursively at any depth.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    // helper
    const findLeafPaths = (o, path = [[]]) =&gt; 
      typeof o == &#39;object&#39; &amp;&amp; !(Array.isArray(o))
        ? Object .entries (o) .flatMap (
            ([k, v]) =&gt; findLeafPaths (v, path).map(p =&gt; [k, ...p])
          ) 
        : path

    // main function
    const convert= (obj) =&gt; 
      findLeafPaths (obj) .reduce ((a, ps) =&gt; ({
        ...a, 
        [ps.join(&#39; - &#39;)]: ps .reduce ((o, p) =&gt; (o || {}) [p], obj)
      }), {})

    // demonstration
    const obj = {
      A: { B: [0, 0, 0, 0] },
      D: {
        B: [0, 0, 0, 0],
        C: [0, 0, 0, 0],
        E: {
          F: 42
        }
      }
    }

    console .log (convert (obj))

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

This uses a helper function. `findLeafPaths` finds the paths to all leaf nodes in an object: `findLeafPaths({a: {b: {c: 1, d: 2, e: 3}, f: 4}, g: 5})` returns `[[&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;], [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;d&#39;], [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;e&#39;], [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;f&#39;], [&#39;g&#39;]]`.  The main function uses this to find the leaf paths, join them into a single string and create an object that has those keys associated with the appropriate value from your original object.

You could take a dynamic approach for any dept of nested objects by storing the path and base object and the actual object.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    function deleteNested(object, path = [], base = object) {
        Object.entries(object).forEach(([k, v]) =&gt; {
            if (v &amp;&amp; typeof v === &#39;object&#39; &amp;&amp; !Array.isArray(v)) {
                deleteNested(v, [...path, k], base);
            } else {
                base[[...path, k].join(&#39; - &#39;)] = v;
                delete base[path[0]];
            }
        });
    }

    const obj = { A: { B: [0, 0, 0, 0] }, D: { B: [0, 0, 0, 0], C: [0, 0, 0, 0] } };

    deleteNested(obj);
    console.log(obj);
&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;
    .as-console-wrapper { max-height: 100% !important; top: 0; }
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

